The patient is a woman with a past medical history of migraines, immune thrombocytopenia (ITP), antiphospholipid antibody syndrome, and hypertension, who presents for neurological evaluation of recurrent episodic events. The semiology is highly suggestive of a seizure disorder. Events are stereotyped and include three distinct patterns: 1) mild episodes with dissociative sensory phenomena (e.g., time distortion, visual flickering) lasting ~5 minutes; 2) moderate episodes with similar auras plus right arm clonic movements and altered mental status; and 3) severe episodes characterized by convulsive movements, back and neck spasms, and post-event confusion, with occasional amnesia. The initial presentation featured automatisms (repetitive refrigerator opening) with amnesia, followed by possible focal to bilateral tonic-clonic activity. The presence of antiphospholipid antibody syndrome raises the possibility of a structural (e.g., ischemic) etiology for an epileptogenic focus. While migraine aura and psychogenic non-epileptic seizures have been considered in the differential, the totality of symptoms—including clear focal onset, motor manifestations, altered awareness, and post-ictal features—strongly favors an epileptic basis. The immediate plan involves definitive characterization under neurology service, with subsequent initiation of appropriate antiseizure medication, taking into account her extensive medication allergies to ensure therapeutic safety.

